<ArticleLayout
  title="Nappy Change Station Checklist"
  description="A checklist for setting up a nappy changing area at home without buying more than the routine needs."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="6 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery room with timber furniture, soft lighting and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    A nappy change station does not need to look like a display nursery. It needs to work
    during normal household moments: overnight changes, rushed mornings, laundry days, after a
    bath, or when you are changing the baby in a bedroom, nursery or living room.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep the supplies close, leave enough room to change a nappy without moving five things
    first, and make cleaning up straightforward enough that the area does not stay messy.
  </p>
  <p>
    This checklist is for Australian families planning a nappy changing area at
    home, whether that is a dedicated change table, a dresser with a change mat, or a portable
    caddy used across more than one room.
  </p>

  <h2>What the change area needs to do</h2>
  <p>
    Buy for the routine you have now, not the perfect nursery layout you imagined before the
    baby arrived.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some households use one fixed change area. Others keep nappies in a caddy and change the
    baby wherever the day is happening. A good setup should support frequent changes, spare
    clothes, wipes, creams, cleaning and laundry without turning the room into a pile of baby
    supplies.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start small, then add storage only when you know what keeps running out, getting lost or
    ending up in the wrong room.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose the change spot first</h2>
  <p>
    The change spot should suit the room and the person doing most of the changing. In some
    homes that means a change table in the nursery. In others, it means a change mat on a
    dresser, a portable mat in the bedroom, or a small caddy near the lounge during the day.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying furniture or storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where most changes are likely to happen.</li>
    <li>Whether nappies and wipes can sit within adult reach.</li>
    <li>Whether there is room for spare clothes.</li>
    <li>Whether the surface is easy to wipe or cover.</li>
    <li>Whether dirty clothes and linen have somewhere to go.</li>
    <li>Whether the setup blocks drawers, wardrobes or walkways.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the nursery is small, a portable caddy may be more useful than another piece of
    furniture. For a fuller guide to the room, see{" "}
    <a href="/guides/baby-change-station-setup-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">Baby Change Station Setup</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep daily supplies close</h2>
  <p>
    The change area works best when the supplies used most often are easy to grab without searching
    through drawers.
  </p>
  <p>Useful everyday items include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Nappies.</li>
    <li>Wipes.</li>
    <li>Barrier cream if used.</li>
    <li>Spare clothes.</li>
    <li>Small bags or a bin system for dirty items.</li>
    <li>Burp cloths or small towels.</li>
    <li>A wipeable mat or washable cover.</li>
    <li>A nearby laundry basket or hamper.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Store bulk nappies, next-size clothes and spare wipes nearby but not necessarily on the
    changing surface. Keeping the immediate area clear makes the routine easier to repeat.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide where dirty items will go</h2>
  <p>
    Nappy changes create small mess often. The setup should make it obvious where dirty
    clothes, used wipes, empty packaging and washable covers go next.
  </p>
  <p>Think about:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where dirty clothes will go.</li>
    <li>Where washable covers or towels will dry or be washed.</li>
    <li>How often nappies and wipes need restocking.</li>
    <li>Whether the bin or bag system is easy to empty.</li>
    <li>Whether creams, bags and small items have a contained place.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A small basket for laundry and a simple restock habit can be more useful than extra
    drawers. The aim is to reset the area quickly, not build a complicated system.
  </p>

  <h2>If space is tight</h2>
  <p>
    Small bedrooms, shared nurseries and rentals may not have room for a full change table.
    In those cases, focus on portable and compact storage.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Use a nappy caddy for supplies that move between rooms.</li>
    <li>Keep spare clothes in one drawer or basket.</li>
    <li>Use drawer dividers for small clothing and creams.</li>
    <li>Store bulk supplies in a wardrobe, laundry or nearby cupboard.</li>
    <li>Choose washable, removable storage that can move as the room changes.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For compact room ideas, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/nursery-storage-small-rooms/">nursery storage guide</a> covers smaller
    rooms, rentals, wardrobes and supplies near the change area in more detail.
  </p>

  <h2>When a dedicated change table can wait</h2>
  <p>
    A dedicated change table can be helpful, but it is not the only way to create a practical
    change station.
  </p>
  <p>It may be worth waiting if:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The nursery layout is still changing.</li>
    <li>The baby is mostly changed in another room.</li>
    <li>You already have a suitable dresser or surface.</li>
    <li>There is not enough room to move around extra furniture.</li>
    <li>A portable caddy would suit the household better.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you do use a mat, dresser or furniture item for changing, follow the manufacturer's
    setup and use instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple nappy change station checklist</h2>
  <p>Before adding more storage near the change area, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where most changes happen during the day and overnight.</li>
    <li>Whether nappies and wipes are easy for adults to reach.</li>
    <li>Whether spare clothes are close enough.</li>
    <li>Whether the changing surface is easy to wipe or cover.</li>
    <li>Whether dirty clothes and covers have a laundry spot.</li>
    <li>Whether bulk supplies can live somewhere else.</li>
    <li>Whether the room still has clear movement around furniture.</li>
    <li>Whether the setup can be reset quickly after each change.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Keep it flexible</h2>
  <p>
    A good nappy change station is less about matching nursery furniture and more about
    making a repeated routine easier.
  </p>
  <p>
    Begin with nappies, wipes, spare clothes, cleaning and laundry. Keep the setup flexible,
    especially in the first months, and only add furniture or organisers when they solve a
    real problem in the room you actually use.
  </p>

